<TITLE> Indonesian separatist leader jailed for life </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 JAKARTA, April 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A court in Indonesia's Maluku province has jailed a separatist leader for life for leading a group of rebels who danced and waved a separatist flag during a presidential visit last year, a court official said on Friday. Nineteen other rebels who took part in the protest were jailed for between 10 and 20 years for treason in verdicts passed on Thursday, said court spokesman Amin Safrudin. The rebels belong to the outlawed South Maluku Republic which proclaimed independence in the Maluku islands 51 years ago after Indonesia became independent from the Dutch. The mainly-Christian group is thought to have little support there and its leaders mostly live in the Netherlands. During the incident in June 2007, the separatists performed a traditional war dance and unfurled a separatist flag in front of President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, who was overseeing an official ceremony in the provincial capital Ambon. The incident was major embarrassment to the president and prompted the replacement of the heads of the provincial police and military. Johan Teterisa was given a life sentence because he was the mastermind of the protest, Safrudin said. "It was his idea to dance in front of the president," he said. The Malukus, 2,300 km (1,440 miles) east of Jakarta, saw vicious fighting between Muslims and Christians from 1999 to 2002 that killed more than 5,000. The conflict also drew Muslim militants from other Indonesian regions. Since a 2002 truce between Muslim and Christian communities, sectarian violence has largely subsided on the islan
